But nor can reason, if themselves have raised
The wretched buildings, for the toil account, Nor tell why thus for hunger, and disease, And shivering cold they thirst, or aught besides
Of ill the body to the soul supplies.
Yet grant them anxious for such vile abodes, Still must the structure far exceed their powers, Hence reared not by themselves.
Nor from without Could they insinuate into bodies formed;
Since nor adapted to their sinuous pores, Nor framed for intercourse, and mutual act.
Whence springs the fury that pervades throughout
