And, at times, E'en while awake, with vigour he pursues Vain semblances of deer as though themselves Started before him, till the phantoms void Vanish at length, and truth regain her sway.
E'en the soft lap-dog his inglorious sleep Breaks not unfrequent, rousing all erect, Urged by the semblance of some face unknown.
And as of harsher seeds the trains are formed
Of floating phantoms, with augmented force Strike they the mind.
Hence birds, with flight abrupt, Oft to the centre of the sacred groves
